TICK-BORNE DISEASES - USA (02): (NORTH DAKOTA) BORRELIA BURGDORFERI, ANAPLASMA PHAGOCYTOPHILUM PREVALENCE IN TICKS
******************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 12 Sep 2014
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research & Policy) News [edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2014/09/news-scan-sep-12-2014


A survey conducted in North Dakota in 2010 found the ticks that carry Lyme disease bacteria (_Ixodes scapularis_, or deer ticks), marking their 1st known appearance in the state and showing that they are spreading westward, according to a study in the September [2014] Journal of Medical Entomology [1].

The researchers collected 1762 ticks through sampling at sites in 9 counties around North Dakota in the early summer of 2010. Most of the ticks (82 percent) were _Dermacentor variabilis_, but 17 percent were _I. scapularis_, found in 6 eastern counties.

In one county (Grand Forks), 3 _I. scapularis_ ticks tested positive for _Borrelia burgdorferi_, the bacterium that causes Lyme disease. Another 8 ticks in the county were infected with _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_, which causes anaplasmosis.

The report notes that Lyme disease cases were rare in North Dakota before 2007 but have increased somewhat since then, with most reported in eastern counties.

"This is the 1st report of _I. scapularis_ and associated pathogens occurring in North Dakota and provides evidence for continued westward expansion of this important vector tick species in the United States," the report says.

