Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The news report above refers to the recent publication
Russart NM, Dougherty MW, Vaughan JA: Survey of Ticks (Acari: Ixodidae) and Tick-Borne Pathogens in North Dakota. J Med Entomol. 2014; 51(5): 1087-90; doi: 10.1603/ME14053; http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1603%2FME14053.

Abstract
--------
"Ticks were sampled at 9 locations throughout North Dakota during early summer of 2010, using flagging techniques and small mammals trapping. In total, 1762 ticks were collected from 8 of the 9 locations. The dominant species were _Dermacentor variabilis_ (Say) (82 percent), found throughout the state, and _Ixodes scapularis_ (Say) (17 percent), found in northeastern counties. A few nymphal and adult _I. scapularis_ tested positive for _Borrelia burgdorferi_ (3 percent) and _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_ (8 percent). This is the 1st report of _I. scapularis_ and associated pathogens occurring in North Dakota and provides evidence for continued westward expansion of this important vector tick species in the United States."

North Dakota, which had no cases of Lyme disease in 2004, had between 8 and 22 confirmed cases reported annually since 2007 (http://www.cdc.gov/lyme/stats/chartstables/reportedcases_statelocality.html). In 2013, 12 confirmed cases of Lyme disease were reported in North Dakota. Since Lyme disease is reported by county of residence, not acquisition, some of these cases could have been imported into the state when a North Dakota resident was on vacation in a Lyme endemic state. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2771447,236.]
